>Hair of the dog
https://pastebin.com/QeMG86Kp

It is a classic story I am sure many of you have read. Art of her can be found in the pic related. Anyways, the main question I want to ask is “Do you believe that the night Volfa and Anon met was her first Sexual Experience?”. I believe that the answer is yes. Now let me say, I don’t usually care if the anthro is a virgin or sexually inexperience, but this story is an exception, for I believe it makes the most sense with Volfa’s character. She never mentions or hints at any past sexual experiences or relationships. The biggest details that warrant this question is how raunchy, unsubtle, and confident Volfa was about sex. She never hesitated once in being sexual with “Little Red”. This was one of alfa’s first stories here and he has stated the events were rushed and characterization was not as good as in “Happiest Place on Fur”. Now I don’t believe that every sexually inexperienced gal has the be a blushing virgin, but a lot of people in writing tend to think so when virginity is a central point of the story and their is a lot of stories in the masterbin that have anthro with Volfa’s confidence, but they make it more obvious with off had quotes like “that was pretty good for my first time”. I like to think her confidence and bravado is the result of her infatuation with “Little Red” and her confident raunchy demeanor was ever only around “Little Red”.

On the get /FIT/ Front: Start with bodybuilding first and foremost. A higher red-muscle mass will increase your resting metabolic rate and help you shed fat faster (the rule of Calories in < Calories out still applies). Start with a 'get back in the gym' plan that includes 5 lifts. Do 2 sets of 12 reps, and do this with different exercises 2 times a week for the first week. Over the next 2 weeks, increase the number of days you go and exercises you do by 1/week. On week 4, increase the number of sets to 3. On week 5, decrease reps to ~10, and increase weight to match. This ramp should minimize DOMS (Delayed Onset Muscle Soreness) while still letting you ramp in aggressively. Key to getting and staying motivated in the first month is minimizing after-workout pain and maximizing "starter's gains".

GET MORE SLEEP THIS IS KEY TO MAKING EVERYTHING ELSE WORK!!!!!

For your diet, start with simple shit and build from there. Cut one bad thing out of your diet to start (E.G. go from soda to UNSWEET tea). When this change becomes part of your daily life (I.E. you don't notice it any more), then make the next change. You don't want to play crash diet games. They'll set you up for failure and make you hate your goals. Life changes are how REAL results happen and stay happen, and they need to be things you can stand to do for, like, the rest of your life.

For no Fap? Just quit looking at porn cold turkey. Honest to God, there's no good way to 'ramp down'. You just need to gut it out the first week, or two, then you're good. Sadly, that'll probably include here for a while. Don't worry, we'll be around when you get your shit back under control and are ready to make the odd conjugal visit.

Oh, shit! if that's the case, you're going to want to do the opposite of what I was saying before, but in the same manner. Little changes you can live with for the duration. If you're having trouble putting muscle on, focus on tactical eating! You don't need to go full gym-rat and choke down $100+ of supplements/month or eat 6 perfectly portioned meals a day, but you still want to follow some simple rules.

Don't let your body think it's starving, or work it on empty. Be sure to bump sugar before and after workouts, so you don't crash during or hurt muscle growth afterwards. Have a banana or something similar beforehand, and a protein shake + fruit (or granola bar) after workouts. There are plenty of good proteins out there for cheap, just do your homework on where they're coming from.

If you possibly can, try to make breakfast a real part of your day. If you like eggs, they're about as good as it gets for this. a dozen only cost, like, $2, and 2-3 of the little bastards is a full-on meal. If you like scrambled, even with some fresh veggies thrown in, they only take 1 skillet, one cutting board, and ~15min to no prep.

Last but not least, learn to love your complex carbs, oils, and proteins. You want to keep your blood sugar level elevated but not spikey, and this is the easiest way to do it. Long grain rice, potatoes, chicken, pork chops, steak... all of these are good things to eat, and

Also, if you're an ectomorph (naturally skinny), know that it'll be a JOURNEY, but one worth making. expect to see 1-2lbs gain/MONTH, if you want it to be sustainable. Sucks in the short term, but it's worth it in the long term. Trust me on that last part. A year from now, you might not feel like a Greek God, but you'll look back in astonishment at the difference.

Hmm... you're probably going to have to work on finding out what works best for you. I've seen skinny folks respond better to high rep workouts (trying to burn it down with lighter weight) and those that have been successful with maximal tension (low rep, high weight). Until you reach your first plateau, I'd stick with the former, and leverage some machine work. for the first month(s), just getting into the gym and doing something is going to make a huge difference. Once you're comfortable in the gym (and it's something you've made a habit) experiment! Try a couple of different things (high rep vs. high weight, isolation vs. compound, even a mix/match approach). Give an approach 3 weeks minimum to start working. Figure out what works for you and ride that trend until it stops working.

Some good background for eating: https://www.muscleandstrength.com/articles/ectomorph-muscle-building-nutrition

^^^DO NOT START OUT WITH THIS WORKOUT PLAN. It's set up for folks who are already gym rats, and already have their technique down for a number of medium to high-risk lifts.

I'm trying to find a good plan, and not coming up with one immediately. Just look around. Find some workouts you ACTUALLY want to do (1-2/muscle group/day) and go do them.

Adding in from another side:
I haven't had much time for exercise the last 18 months. Add in a mini ulcer and other GI issues that have me bloated and I look like I've run off the rails.
On the other hand, I focused mainly on varied low rep, high weight, high volume techniques. Combine that with a high baseline level of activity and I've retained a lit of strength.
If I can ever unfuck my schedule, and my metabolism, getting back in shape is just effort.

What you choose do do now has far reaching effects. You're making life easier on future you, but only if you avoid catastrophic injury.
You'll get hurt. It'll suck.
A strong back and legs will retain your ability to be active as you age.

Bloodflow is everything. You heal faster, drop fat faster, have less erectile issues or preventable health issues. How you get there will change over the years. Doing something, even the small things, is better than nothing.
Kind of like writing.
